<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="477" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,604,1135]" pageId="6" pageNumber="477">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1037,1063]" pageId="6" pageNumber="477">Remarks.</emphasis>
Male terminalia was originally described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Sasakawa, M." box="[829,1024,1036,1063]" pageId="6" pageNumber="477" pagination="40 - 44" refId="ref7462" refString="Sasakawa, M. (1986) Two new species of the genus Cordilura Fallen (Diptera, Scatophagidae) from Japan. Proceedings of the Japanese Society of Systematic Zoology, 33, 40 - 44." type="journal article" year="1986">Sasakawa (1986)</bibRefCitation>
, and redescribed and figured by 
<bibRefCitation author="Ozerov, A. L. &amp; Krivosheina, M. G." pageId="6" pageNumber="477" pagination="1 - 4" refId="ref7146" refString="Ozerov, A. L. &amp; Krivosheina, M. G. (2012 b) To the knowledge of the genus Cordilura Fallen, 1810 (Diptera, Scathophagidae), with description of a new species from the Russian Far East. Far Eastern Entomologist, 249, 1 - 4. https: // doi. org / 10.25221 / fee. 353.1" type="journal article" year="2012">Ozerov &amp; Krivosheina (2012b)</bibRefCitation>
in detail. This species resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="(Fallen)" baseAuthorityName="Fallen" baseAuthorityYear="1819" box="[855,1067,1072,1099]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Cordilura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="477" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albipes">
<emphasis box="[855,970,1072,1099]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="477">C. albipes</emphasis>
(Fallén)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Sasakawa" authorityName="Sasakawa" authorityYear="1986" box="[1124,1388,1072,1099]" class="Insecta" family="Muscidae" genus="Cordilura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="477" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cuspidata">
<emphasis box="[1124,1267,1072,1099]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="477">C. cuspidata</emphasis>
Sasakawa
</taxonomicName>
, but differs from them by the characteristics as mentioned above.
</paragraph>
